<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / Monklands Labour candidate slams council spending 'bias'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mrs Helen Liddell, the Labour candidate in the Monklands East by-election
caused by the death of John Smith, said yesterday she would fight to rectify
the bias in the allocation of spending by the district council towards one
part of the district.
She confronted the most explosive issue of the campaign for Labour - the
long-standing allegation that Labour-controlled Monklands district council
favours the town of Coatbridge at the expense of next-door Airdrie in its
capital spending. Airdrie is at the centre of Monklands East constituency,
near Glasgow, where polling takes place next Thursday.
The issue, sometimes known as Monklandsgate, has been simmering since late
1992. Newspapers and dissident Labour councillors allege that a clique on
the council - the 'Monklands Mafia' - favours predominantly Roman Catholic
Coatbridge over Protestant Airdrie.
It is also alleged that over several years a dominant group of Labour
councillors, who are mainly Catholic, allocated 40 council jobs to their
relatives.
Mrs Liddell, having initially tried to stay aloof from the issue, wrote to
the council on Tuesday asking for a breakdown of capital spending between
Coatbridge and Airdrie, which are of similar size. After receiving the
figures she said they proved that spending was concentrated on Coatbridge.
They showed that between 1982 and 1992 Coatbridge received Pounds 18.8m on
'strategic projects', while Airdrie received nothing. Other capital spending
was Pounds 49.8m on Airdrie and Pounds 51m on Coatbridge. Strategic projects
include a leisure centre, country park, heritage park and council offices,
all located in Coatbridge.
Mrs Liddell said yesterday she wanted an explanation of the discrepancy
between the council's figures and those collected by four dissident Labour
councillors for the years 1989 to 1992, which showed 'a more marked
difference' between the two towns in non-strategic spending. On this
analysis Airdrie received Pounds 2.2m and Coatbridge Pounds 3.7m.
She said: 'I'm determined to make sure that Airdrie, the outlying villages
and the Coatbridge parts of the constituency are receiving their fair share
of spending.'
The acknowledgement by Mrs Liddell, who is a former secretary of the
Scottish Labour party and was a close associate of John Smith, of
shortcomings in the local council was seized on by the other candidates.
Mrs Kay Ullrich, the Scottish National party candidate, said the electorate
would not be duped by Mrs Liddell's 'amazing conversion'.
Mrs Susan Bell, the Conservative candidate, said Mrs Liddell's words
vindicated what the Tories had been saying.
</TEXT>
