<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / Telegraph cuts price to 30p in fight with Times
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Conrad Black declared war in Britain's broadsheet newspaper market last
night by cutting the weekday cover price of the Daily Telegraph from 48p to
30p. The move brings the price of the newspaper down to that of The Times,
which was reduced to 30p in September.
'This is war and no one goes to war in other than a sober mood but we are
market leader and we will protect our position,' said Mr Black, the
Telegraph's chairman.
Last night, The Independent reacted by cutting the price of the newspaper
from 50p to 20p - but for today only. It said it would review pricing
policy.
The Telegraph's retaliation came after 10 months of insisting it would not
match the price of The Times. But in April the Telegraph's circulation
dipped below 1m for the first time in more than 40 years. There was a
further fall in May to 993,395 as The Times reached record sales of 515,000.
Mr Black said Telegraph sales were now above 1m but he was not 'going to sit
like a suet pudding' and allow any competitor to attack his share of the
market.
The move will cost the Daily Telegraph Pounds 40m in a full year, and Mr
Black admitted there would be an effect on profits 'for some years',
although much of the cost would be offset by cost-cutting and tax relief.
The board said it intended to maintain current dividend levels.
Less than two weeks ago, Mr Black told the annual meeting of Hollinger,
whose interests include 57 per cent of the Telegraph group, that circulation
of the Daily and Sunday Telegraph was 'quite satisfactory' in spite of
cut-price competition.
But he said he would consider 'remedial action' if The Times' circulation
rose to more than half that of the Telegraph.
The price of the Saturday edition and the Sunday Telegraph will remain at
70p each, although the group has a weekend offer of the two for Pounds 1.
Mr Max Hastings, editor-in-chief of the Telegraph said: 'The Daily Telegraph
readers have remained extremely loyal, with 96 per cent continuing to
purchase the paper despite the dramatic price cutting activities elsewhere.'
Mr Black said last night that when Hollinger sold Telegraph shares worth
Pounds 73m on May 20 he had no intention of cutting the paper's price, but
May circulation figures had changed his mind.
Black aims to win, Page 8
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
