<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / Clinton defiant over dollar's fall: US currency steady -
Investors urged to concentrate on 'strong fundamentals'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE and PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton responded defiantly yesterday to downward pressure on
the dollar in global financial markets, urging investors to pay more
attention to strong US economic fundamentals.
'This is the first time in 30 years that we have had growth in the economy
with no inflation led by investment that will create jobs,' he said.
Mr Clinton's remarks were reinforced by upbeat comments on the US economy by
Mr Alan Greenspan, Federal Reserve chairman, and Mr Lloyd Bentsen, US
Treasury secretary. Their concerted remarks followed overnight intervention
by the Bank of Japan and combined to help the dollar and stock and bond
markets.
But in Tokyo, Mr Hirohisa Fujii, Japan's finance minister, warned that
'rapid fluctuations' in exchange rates 'would do harm not only to the
Japanese economy but to the world economy'. The Japanese government had
called an emergency cabinet meeting to discuss the yen's renewed strength.
Early today in Tokyo the dollar, which had dipped below Y100 on Tuesday, was
quoted at Y101.5, as bankers reported renewed intervention by the Japanese
central bank immediately after the opening.
The dollar's bright start in Tokyo this morning continued a firmer trend
begun yesterday in London, where it closed at Y100.695. In New York it
finished at Y100.95.
The US currency also steadied against the D-Mark, finishing at DM1.6006 in
London and DM1.60535 in New York after dropping below DM1.59 in the previous
session.
On Wall Street, the Dow Jones Industrial Average ended the day 16.8 up at
3,724.77, its first advance in three sessions.
The benchmark US long bond was trading up  29/32 by early afternoon at 86
3/32 . It closed at 86 9/32 , pushing the yield down to 7.397.
Mr Clinton gave no sign of wanting to change domestic policies in response
to external financial pressures.
'We'll just have to keep working on our fundamentals and know that in the
end the markets will have to respond to the economic realities,' he said.
The US is in its fourth year of a steady economic expansion. The
unemployment rate has fallen to 6 per cent and the annual inflation rate is
less than 3 per cent. Most countries are still struggling to emerge from
recession.
Behind Mr Clinton's words is the confidence that the US economy is less
vulnerable to damage from currency volatility than most countries because
the share of trade in gross domestic product remains low.
Mr Clinton's claim that US economic achievements were being undervalued was
echoed both by Mr Greenspan and Mr Bentsen. The Treasury secretary said he
was 'concerned by recent movements in the exchange markets'. The US and its
Group of Seven partners would 'continue to be prepared to act as
appropriate' - a veiled reference to possible concerted intervention by
central banks in support of the dollar.
Speaking on Capitol Hill, Mr Greenspan said the economic outlook was 'as
bright as it has been in decades. Economic activity has strengthened,
unemployment is down, and price trends have remained subdued.'
Mr Greenspan said many investors were too pessimistic about the outlook for
US inflation. Long bond yields were 'higher than they should be' because
they embodied an excessive 'inflation premium'.
European bond and stock markets took some comfort from the more stable
dollar and from Mr Greenspan's testimony.
In Frankfurt, the Dax stock market index rose 11.15 in normal trading hours
to 1,994.42. After hours, it added another 10 to 2,004.93. In Paris, the CAC
Index jumped 26.26 to 1917.04. In London, markets were also given a boost by
the publication of the minutes of the May meeting between Mr Kenneth Clarke,
chancellor, and Mr Eddie George, governor of the Bank of England.
The minutes indicated that the authorities saw no immediate need to increase
UK interest rates. The FT-SE 100 Index recovered some of its recent losses,
rising 20.2 to 2,960.4, while the September long gilt future gained nearly
two points.
Anxious Japanese fearful of yen's strength Page 4
Greenspan seeks to allay inflation fear Page 7
Treasury minutes Page 11
Editorial Comment Page 21
Rocky road offers no respite for bonds Page 23
International bonds Page 31
Currencies Page 33
World stocks Page 39
London shares Page 42
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
