<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / International Company News: Lotus remains confident despite
fall in share price
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Lotus Development plunged by more than a quarter in New York
yesterday morning following the US software group's gloomy sales and profits
projections the night before.
The heavy selling came in the wake of growing disenchantment in the
investment community in recent months, prompted by slowing sales of the
company's applications software products, which account for 70 per cent of
revenues. At the close of trading the shares were Dollars 37, down Dollars
14 3/8 . This capitalised the shares at less than half the level reached at
their peak in mid-March, when it they were valued at Dollars 3.9bn.
Lotus continued to maintain yesterday that its long-term prospects remained
unaffected by the profits warning. It blamed the share price fall on its
failure to meet market expectations for one quarter. 'We've sinned in that
regard,' said Mr Robert Schechter, senior vice-president for international
business. 'But over the long run, we feel very, very confident.' He said
that the company's fast-growing communications software products, which
already account for 30 per cent of sales, continued to experience growth
which was 'at or ahead of expectations'.
The Massachusetts-based company had warned that sales in the second quarter,
to the end of June, would be Dollars 230m-Dollars 240m, roughly level with
the previous year, and that earnings per share would be 20-25 cents. Most
analysts had been expecting close to 50 cents a share. It revised its
earnings per share projection for the year as a whole to Dollars
1.80-Dollars 2, down from its earlier forecast of Dollars 2-Dollars 2.15.
The company said the sales fall-off was due to delays in the release of a
number of upgrades to its biggest applications software products, including
1-2-3, a spreadsheet package, and Approach, a database product. This was
caused by development delays, related to difficulties in integrating the
various products and integrating them with the company's popular Notes
communications software.
Lotus' shares are now back at the level last seen at the end of last summer.
Their run-up through to March was based on optimism over the company's
communications software, one field where it is regarded as being ahead of
arch-rival Microsoft.
</TEXT>
