<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / International Company News: Partner sought for Cologne Re
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER and ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Colonia, Germany's third biggest insurance group, confirmed yesterday that
it was holding talks which could lead to an international strategic alliance
for Cologne Re, its reinsurance subsidiary.
Mr Claas Kleyboldt, Colonia's chairman, said that the talks were taking
place with a number of companies but that as yet there was no preferred
partner for the match. He was speaking in Cologne as Colonia - now a
subsidiary of the French Union des Assurances de Paris (UAP) - reported
pre-tax profits up by nearly a quarter for 1993.
He stressed that under no circumstances would Colonia sell its 75 per cent
direct and indirect holding in Cologne Re, nor would it contemplate a full
merger with another party. The only requirement was that the partner pursued
a similar strategy to that of the German company, Kleyboldt said.
He refused to comment on reports that the company, the fourth largest
reinsurance group in the world with gross income of DM4.5bn (Dollars 2.8bn)
in 1992, would forge links with either General Corp Re or Employers
Reinsurance Corp, two US reinsurance companies.
Although the talks are apparently at an early stage, they highlight the move
towards co-operation and consolidation in the global reinsurance industry.
Last week, for example, Suez, the French holding company, agreed to sell
Abeille Re, its French reinsurer, to Scor, France's largest reinsurance
group, as part of the disposal of the Victoire group of insurance
businesses. The deal valued the reinsurer at more than FFr2bn (Dollars
366m).
UAP confirmed that in principle it would not be opposed to Cologne Re
forming a strategic alliance with an international partner in the
reinsurance field.
Neither General Re nor Employers Reinsurance could be contacted immediately
for comment yesterday.
</TEXT>
