<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / International Company News: Philip Morris chiefs committed
to change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The new bosses of Philip Morris, the US food and tobacco group, yesterday
promised a sharp change in management style in an effort to restore growth
to the company's flagging share price.
Mr William Murray, who took over from Mr Michael Miles as chairman at the
weekend, said: 'I want to say categorically that we are not committed to
doing things in the way they were done in the past. I want to emphasise that
point.'
Mr Murray and Mr Geoffrey Bible, who took over Mr Miles's role as chief
executive, were speaking in New York just three days after their promotion
to the top two jobs at Philip Morris following Mr Miles's sudden
resignation.
Mr Murray said their overriding priority would be to produce rates of
earnings growth that compared 'very favourably' with the rest of corporate
America.
All the group's businesses were performing well, and the domestic and
international tobacco businesses 'had never been stronger,' he said.
Superior earnings growth would produce superior cash flow, and this is turn
would give Philip Morris the flexibility to consider a wide range of options
for improving shareholder value. These could include a bigger share buy-back
programme, bigger dividends, strategic acquisitions or debt reduction.
Mr Murray confirmed that an earlier plan to demerge the tobacco businesses -
seen by some as having brought about Mr Miles's demise - was off the table.
He said structural changes to the company would always be considered if they
enhanced shareholder value, 'but I do not think we will be making any
announcements soon regarding separation or other forms of structure'.
Mr Murray Green, Philip Morris's general counsel, said a demerger of the
tobacco business had been abandoned because of the danger that it would be
challenged in the courts as a fraudulent conveyance by those seeking damages
from the group over smoking-related diseases.
Mr Bible sought to play down the legal and political challenges facing
Philip Morris over its tobacco operations in the US. 'We are confident that
all of these remain manageable,' he said.
'On the litigation front the good news is that there is really no new news
there. There are some new and experienced plaintiff lawyers, there are some
novel approaches, but we also have extremely talented and experienced
counsel working for us,' he said. 'And you must remember that we have never
lost a case.'
On the Washington front, Mr Bible played down challenges to the tobacco
industry as the rhetoric of 'a handful of anti-tobacco legislators'.
</TEXT>
