<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / UK Company News: Wessex Water rises 20% and meets
expectations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fears that a false market in water shares would be created by leaks of
forthcoming price increases appeared unfounded as Wessex Water ended the
industry's results season yesterday.
Wessex met expectations with a 20 per cent increase in annual pre-tax
profits to Pounds 103.3m and a 9.3 per cent dividend rise to 23.5p.
This included a final pay-out of 15.5p, up by 9 per cent. Sales increased by
6 per cent to Pounds 217.2m for the year to March 31.
Analysts expressed relief that there had been no leaks of the discussions
water companies are having with the industry regulator Ofwat on price
increases for the next five years.
The companies had received draft increases at the end of May, but the
figures will not be published until July 28.
This had prompted complaints to Ofwat and the Stock Exchange that
speculation could have led to a false market.
The season showed water companies concerned above all with cost-cutting and
treasury management. This will be increasingly important under the stricter
pricing regime promised by the regulator. Companies will have to live with
lower price increases, while facing increased capital commitments because of
regulation and environmental concerns.
On average, analysts said, costs rose by about 2 per cent against almost 6
per cent a year between 1990 and 1993.
Wessex scored highly on cost control yesterday, showing a 2 per cent decline
at the operational level. After allowing for higher depreciation, costs were
held at Pounds 125m.
The group's profits were boosted by a doubled contribution from the joint
venture with Waste Management International.
Wessex intended to continue pursuing acquisitions in the waste management
division, having completed eight last year. Some Pounds 65m remained to fund
expansion.
The core utility increased operating profits by 14 per cent to Pounds 92.2m.
Wessex ended the year with net cash of Pounds 39m.
Fully diluted earnings per share rose to 60.4p from 60.1p. The shares closed
down 17p at 586p.
See Lex
