<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / Eurodollar latest to delay issue as shares fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON and PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This week's fall in share prices has created further turmoil in the new
issue market, with Eurodollar postponing its Pounds 100m flotation and a
number of smaller issues being pulled.
Eurodollar, the UK's second-largest car rental company, had planned to issue
its prospectus and pricing details today.
But the group, the subject of a management buy-out from TSB last year, said
that 'in the light of market conditions, it would be appropriate to delay
impact day for a short period'.
The company emphasised that the flotation had been postponed rather than
abandoned and said that book-building with institutional investors was
continuing.
Eurodollar follows British Printing Company, which recently postponed its
Pounds 250m stock market debut. Other casualties include property group
London Capital Holdings and three cable companies.
But it is smaller companies that have proved most vulnerable to the market
downturn. Yesterday the planned Pounds 13.5m flotation of bingo halls group
Jasmine was called off.
The float, which was being handled by Greig Middleton, was already falling
behind schedule and the company said that Monday's stock market slump had
'put the kibosh' on its plans.
The company was a management buy-out from Rank and hoped to raise money to
pay off the buy-out debt.
Pegson, a construction equipment maker, has also postponed its plans for a
placing through Granville Davies, which would have valued it at around
Pounds 12m.
Advisers to Universal Ceramic Materials, whose flotation price was due to be
announced on Thursday, were in meetings last night.
But, apart from Eurodollar, the larger companies that are in the final
run-up to flotation are sticking to their schedules. Exco, the money broker
hoping to float with a Pounds 220m valuation, is still looking to price its
shares next week.
Mr Simon Linnett of sponsors N M Rothschild said: 'We are reasonably
confident that everything will proceed according to plan. The reception from
institutions has been very good and, as 3i has shown, there is still an
appetite for quality new issues.'
Pillar Property Investment also confirmed the timetable for its Pounds 175m
flotation.
</TEXT>
