<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / Thorn EMI music chief gets Pounds 13.5m package
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jim Fifield, who heads Thorn EMI's music business, has trebled his salary
package to about Pounds 13.5m - a figure more than 23 times higher than the
sum paid to the company's chairman, Sir Colin Southgate.
The package includes his Pounds 2.105m basic salary and a Pounds 5.046m
performance-related bonus, of which Pounds 1.5m is in ordinary shares. This
was partly an annual bonus awarded by the board for achieving internal group
targets, and partly from the music division's incentive scheme.
In addition, Mr Fifield received 619,592 ordinary shares free of charge as
compensation for changes to his terms of contract. Thorn refused to comment
on the changes.
At yesterday's closing price of 1034p, Mr Fifield's bonus shares were worth
Pounds 6.4m. However, under the terms of his remuneration agreement, the
shares cannot be sold until March 31 1998.
Mr Fifield's remuneration is revealed in the latest report and accounts. Sir
Colin's package includes a salary of Pounds 474,347 and a Pounds 110,630
bonus, which he took in shares. In the previous year, he received a total of
Pounds 702,759.
Thorn EMI directors' pay and bonuses are decided by a board compensation
committee which is chaired by the group's non-executive deputy chairman, Sir
Peter Walters, formerly head of BP. The committee consists of all the
non-executive directors, including Sir Michael Angus, chairman of Whitbread
and former president of the CBI, Mr David Barnes, chief executive of Zeneca,
and Sir Graham Day, former chairman of Cadbury Schweppes and British
Aerospace.
Leisure analysts expressed surprise at the payments to Mr Fifield, who
earned Pounds 4.7m the previous year. 'Even though the music division has
shown remarkable growth, Fifield's salary has gone a bit overboard,' said
one. However, given the success of the music business and possible
shareholder gains through a demerger, few thought shareholder dissent would
be a serious problem.
Thorn's profits grew from Pounds 273.5m to Pounds 326.5m last year, with the
music division increasing from Pounds 196.9m to Pounds 246.1m.
Thorn is renaming its rental business Thorn Group to differentiate it from
EMI Music, which is based in New York.
