<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / EU unable to provide ministers' voting record
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Council of Ministers, the most powerful European Union institution where
ministers of the 12 member states decide on hundreds of European laws that
are later put on national statute books, is unable to provide records of how
members have voted.
In a letter to the Financial Times turning down a request for voting
records, the general secretariat of the Council says it cannot provide such
records because it does not compile them.
However, the rejection of the request has been contested by the Netherlands
and Denmark, and reservations about the decision have been expressed by the
UK. Ministers' votes are recorded in the minutes of Council meetings. The
Council has refused to release these.
The EU system of qualified majority voting (QMV) brought the UK and Spain
into dispute with their partners this spring in the worst row since the
crisis over ratification of the Maastricht treaty.
However, the often tendentious claims made during that dispute could not be
tested against a public record of how majority voting worked in practice.
Such a record would show that the EU culture of consensus means very few
legislative proposals are put to a vote, in order to avoid isolating member
states. When a vote is taken, Germany, the largest member state, is the
country most often outvoted.
After the spring row, and because the votes dispute will resurface before
the 1996 constitutional review of Maastricht, the Financial Times sought
information on the workings of QMV in decisions made by the Council of
Ministers for foreign affairs, the internal market, social affairs, and
agriculture, dating back to 1989. Under the single-market programme alone,
ministers agreed over 200 Euro-laws during that period, most under the QMV
system.
The FT request was made under the code of conduct on public access to
information, which was established after five successive summits of EU
leaders called for more open government to 'bring Europe closer to the
people'. Most votes taken since the code was passed last December are now
made public.
In reply, on May 31, the general secretariat of the Council said it did 'not
compile voting records' and was unable to supply the information requested.
On June 6, the FT exercised its right to have the rejected request pass from
the Council secretariat to member states.
The member states received the correspondence on June 17, when the low-level
General Affairs Group of the Council tried to push through a second
rejection. That was vetoed by the Dutch and Danes, while the UK sought more
time to consider a change in the appeal procedure.
The draft of the second rejection, obtained by the FT, restated that 'the
general secretariat does not compile lists of voting records and the Council
is not in possession of any such statistics'.
EU fails to keep 'open government' pledge, Page 2
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>LUZ  Luxembourg, EC.
</CN>
