FT  22 JUN 94 / Network plan to inform public
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Information 'superhighways' - advanced communications networks capable of
carrying text and moving video images - are being considered as a means of
disseminating official information to the public.
The government yesterday published a consultation document and said it was
reviewing the possibilities presented by superhighways. The report was
prepared by the government's Central Computers and Telecommunications Agency
for Mr William Waldegrave, the public service minister.
The world's leading telecommunications and computer companies have made
dramatic advances in the development of information highways.
In the US, research to increase the availability and reduce the costs of the
technology for government information purposes is continuing.
Among the possibilities are access to government reports and statistics,
access to job vacancies and checks on citizens' rights.
Information superhighways: Opportunities for Public-Sector Application in
the UK. CCTA. 071 217 3350. Free.
