<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / Trade deficit with non-EU countries widens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK's visible trade deficit with countries outside the European Union
widened to a seasonally adjusted Pounds 767m in May, as imports rose 2.5 per
cent and exports fell 2.5 per cent on the month.
The Central Statistical Office revised down April's deficit to Pounds 493m,
from Pounds 566m. If oil and erratic items, such as ships and precious
stones, are excluded May's deficit was Pounds 669m, compared with Pounds
614m in April.
In the three months to May the visible trade deficit was Pounds 1.95bn,
compared with Pounds 2.09bn in the previous three months.
In volume terms the UK is seeing a modest improvement. In the three months
to May import volumes were 2 per cent lower than in the previous three
months. Export volumes fell 1 per cent. The CSO said that on a trend basis
export volumes were unchanged while imports were falling by  1/2 per cent a
month.
Mr Michael Saunders, UK economist at Salomon Brothers, said: 'The dip in
import volumes is a further sign that suggests that the UK economy is not
accelerating into an unsustainable boom and contrasts with the late 1980s
import surge.'
Yet Mr Sanjay Joshi, head of bond research at Daiwa Europe, said the figures
showed 'a disappointing export performance. The benefit of the competitive
devaluation in September 1992 seems to be fading away'.
Import prices rose faster than export prices in the three months to May,
with the main increase coming in basic materials, which might reflect the
recent rise in world commodity markets. Prices of both exports and imports
have risen 20 per cent since August 1992.
After the recent rise in North Sea production the oil account was once more
in surplus. In the first five months of the year the UK had a Pounds 36m oil
surplus, compared with a Pounds 1.38bn deficit in the calendar year 1993.
The CSO said that in the three months to May there was a sharp rise in
imports from other OECD countries, mainly Japan, Australia and New Zealand.
Exports to North America and the rest of the world rose. Trade with Malaysia
showed little sign of the ban on state contracts for British companies:
exports to Malaysia were Pounds 161m in May, Pounds 110m in April and Pounds
78m in January.
