<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / Big rise in legal aid abuse inquiries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A sharp rise in cases of fraud and abuse of the legal aid scheme was
reported yesterday by the Legal Aid Board.
In its annual report the board, which administers the scheme for the
government, said the number of preliminary investigations undertaken by its
investigation section had risen from 642 in 1992-93 to 1,035 in 1993-94.
The number of cases under investigation also increased from 362 in 1992-93
to 957 in 1993-94.
The board said the rise was largely because of the number of letters sent to
solicitors requiring an explanation of questionable costs claims.
Of the 957 investigations, 836 fell into that category. As a result,
information about 363 firms had been passed to the Solicitors Complaints
Bureau and 21 had been reported to it with a request for disciplinary
action.
The remaining 121 cases involved more detailed investigations. Six cases had
resulted in court appearances, four of which involved solicitors and their
support staff.
Two solicitors and a clerk were convicted and one solicitor acquitted.
The two other cases involved legal aid applicants making false declarations
to obtain aid.
At the end of 1993-94 there were 517 continuing investigations of which 30
had been reported to the police and five were awaiting trial.
The investigation section also dealt with solicitors' firms which, during
the course of investigations, had been found to be over-claiming costs on
the legal aid fund.
A total of Pounds 143,000 had been recovered.
During 1993-94 the board met all but one of its performance targets on
handling aid applications and payment of lawyers' bills, and achieved the
quality assurance standard, BS 5750.
</TEXT>
