<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / Birmingham M-way toll inquiry begins
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The public inquiry which may settle the fate of the first toll motorway
proposed in the UK opened yesterday in Walsall, West Midlands, amid
expectations that it will hear evidence for between six and nine months.
Sir John Fitzpatrick, the government-appointed inspector, heard the opening
statement of the Department of Transport, which wants to build the
Birmingham Northern Relief Road around the northern and eastern sides of the
Birmingham-Black Country conurbation to relieve the M6. The new road would
run through the green belt from the M6 west of Cannock to Coleshill, east of
Birmingham and close to the junction of the M6 with the M42. It would cost
about Pounds 500m and involve the purchase of about 1,500 acres of private
land.
The proposal, which was first made in 1980, has prompted objections from
more than 7,000 people. They include representatives of environmental groups
such as Friends of the Earth; villagers fearing disturbance and
representatives of special-interest lobbies such as the British
Motorcyclists Federation.
The weight of objections will ensure that - as Mr Gwyn Drake, West Midlands
projects director of the Highways Agency, - said: this will be 'one of the
largest public inquiries for years'. It will rival in scale the inquiries
into the M40, the M1-A1 link road and the East London River Crossing.
The inquiry is the second into the relief road. Since the first in 1988, the
government has changed its proposals to bring in private-sector finance.
It has given a 53-year concession to build and operate the road to a joint
venture of Trafalgar House, the UK engineering and construction group, and
Iritecna, the Italian toll motorway operator. They modified the route
slightly from the transport department proposals of the 1980s.
The argument about the need for the road centres on congestion on the M6. Mr
Michael Fitzgerald QC, for the transport department, told the inquiry that
without the new road 'the conditions which are worst on Fridays will become
the norm'.
Friends of the Earth, which claims to have gathered 'the most comprehensive
alliance against any road in this country', will argue that the road would
generate more traffic.
It said: 'It's very important that a message goes to the government that
they can't build motorways through the countryside any more.'
</TEXT>
