<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / Level of grants deter Design Council bidders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government plans to sell the Design Council's industrial services have run
into trouble because private-sector bidders want 'unacceptably' high
government grants.
The Design Council, the government-funded body which provides design
services to industry, is in the throes of a reorganisation which will leave
it with just a quarter of its staff of about 200, and a greatly reduced
budget.
The government's intention is to transfer many existing services to a
regional network of one-stop business service centres, called Business
Links, and for other services to be sold to the private sector.
The industrial services include the Materials Information Service, which
maintains a database of materials and their applications; an 'Innovation
Noticeboard', which helps inventors get their ideas produced and marketed;
and a design-consultancy register, which provides businesses with the names
of approved consultants.
Both the government and the Design Council's management had hoped that the
industrial services could be kept together. A shortlist of four bidders put
forward plans for purchases of the package, on the understanding that some
Department of Trade and Industry funds would be made available through
Business Links. It now appears that there will either be very limited DTI
cash, or none.
Design Council staff were told yesterday that attempts were to be made to
sell the individual services and fresh bids were being invited from the
private sector on that basis.
The staff, through their union MSF, had been campaigning to keep the
services together. There are fears that fragmentation will mean that
individual schemes which do not find private-sector purchasers will be
scrapped.
There is concern among staff that the Business Links network, which has been
slower to get off the ground than the government envisaged, has yet to prove
its interest or commitment to design.
</TEXT>
