<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / Jobseeker benefit deal 'a shambles'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The departments of employment and social security have reached a compromise
over the administration of the new Jobseeker's Allowance.
After months of wrangling it was announced yesterday that the allowance will
be jointly operated by the Employment Service, a Department of Employment
agency; and the Benefits Agency, which comes under the social security
department. Mr Frank Field, Labour chairman of the Commons social security
committee, attacked the deal as a 'shambles' and 'the worst of all possible
fudges'.
The announcement, which unions warned could result in at least 3,000 job
losses, ends weeks of speculation over which department would take
responsibility for the new benefit, which replaces unemployment benefit.
Under the deal, the Employment Service will be responsible for advice and
tests such as availability for work. Financial aspects, including the
calculation and payment of the benefit, will be the responsibility of the
Benefits Agency.
It had been feared that the transfer of the allowance to the DSS might have
weakened the employment department at a time when its future as an
independent department is under discussion.
Mr Field said the arrangement 'couldn't be more unsatisfactory'. It would
have been better, he said, if one department had disbursed all benefits and
at the same time had been responsible for running the job clubs, which are
government-run centres for job seekers.
The allowance, to be introduced in April 1996, will be paid for only six
months, compared with the one year for unemployment benefit. Subsequent
benefits will be means-tested and there will be a greater obligation upon
the individual to seek work.
Mr Donald Dewar, shadow social security secretary, said the reorganisation
of services for the unemployed was 'wrong in principle and damaging in
practice'.
</TEXT>
