<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / Gooda underwriter 'hid from facts'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A former underwriter of the loss-making Gooda Walker syndicates failed to
measure adequately his exposure to potential loss, it was alleged yesterday
in the High Court.
The criticism came in the 20th day of a civil action by 3,095 Lloyd's Names,
the individuals whose wealth supports the insurance market, who are suing
their agents to recover losses of more than Pounds 600m.
Their syndicates were swamped by losses from disasters between 1988 and
1990, including the explosion aboard the Piper Alpha oil platform in the
North Sea and Hurricane Hugo in the Caribbean.
Mr Ulrich von Eicken, appearing as an expert witness for the Names,
dismissed claims by Mr Stanley Andrews, underwriter for syndicate 298, that
the scale of the Piper Alpha oil platform loss was unimaginable. He said
this was 'simply hiding yourself from the facts'.
Mr von Eicken is a former executive with Munich Re, one of the world's
biggest reinsurance companies.
He told the court that Gooda Walker underwriters were wrong to base their
business on the assumption that they would be hit by no catastrophic losses.
'If you are in the catastrophe business you can't possibly base your
activities on there not being a catastrophe,' he said.
Mr Andrews, whose syndicate lost heavily after the disaster, told the court
last week that: 'We never honestly thought that the loss of Piper Alpha
could actually ever occur.'
Mr Andrews' system for measuring his aggregate exposures was 'thoroughly
inadequate', added Mr von Eicken.
Earlier Mr Jonathan Gaisman QC, cross examining Mr Andrews, said Lloyd's
agents had alleged the underwriter 'did not have a clue about what he is
underwriting' and 'did not inspire any confidence whatsoever'.
Other documents cited by Mr Gaisman show that Mr Andrews believed his
syndicate would break even in its 1988 account, months after the Piper loss.
According to the documents, one agent, reporting a meeting with Mr Tony
Gooda, chairman of the Gooda and Partners members' agency, said: 'I asked
whether it was incompetence or the fact that he was pulling the wool over
our eyes. Mr Gooda said regrettably that it was due to incompetence, and
that he and the board were also partly to blame.'
Another agent knew of the scale of Mr Andrews' Piper losses months in
advance of the underwriter.
</TEXT>
