<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / Ashdown moves to attract support from business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Paddy Ashdown last night tried to woo support from British business by
underlining his party's support for a single European currency in a speech
to a Confederation of British Industry dinner in London.
Mr Ashdown said that only the Liberal Democrats among mainstream British
political parties argued that 'if and when' a single currency emerged in the
Europe Union, there was 'no viable future for Britain outside of it'.
Attempting to set out a distinctive Liberal Democrat approach to economic
policy, he said that only his party had consistently advocated operational
independence for the Bank of England. An independent central bank was 'the
cornerstone of an economic policy based on low inflation'.
Making no reference to the party's rejection of Britain's so-called 'opt
out' from Maastricht's social chapter, Mr Ashdown highlighted its opposition
to a national minimum wage - as advocated by Labour.
He said this opposition would be reinforced if such a wage operated 'at the
levels set in countries like France'.
On small business, he said the party supported legislation to tackle the
problem of late commercial debt. The average company was now owed Pounds
145,000 in late debt, he said. 'We have long argued that small businesses
deserve much stronger support from government.'
Mr Ashdown - who is also expected to address the CBI annual conference this
autumn - took pains to differentiate Liberal Democrat policy on full
employment from Labour.
'Unlike Labour we do not promise to deliver full employment,' he said.
'Instead we pursue the goal of full employability.'
</TEXT>
