<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / World Cup '94: Maradona shows glimpses of old skill against
Greece
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Maradona lives: at least Argentina's flawed 33-year-old glory thrived
against an outclassed Greece, scoring a goal and playing all but the last
seven minutes in his team's 4-0 win at Foxboro Stadium, Massachusetts.
He was not the Argentina star of the day. That honour belonged to Gabriel
(the archangel) Batistuta, who achieved the World Cup's first hat-trick - a
second-minute poke through the Greek goalkeeper's legs, a 43rd-minute right
foot blast from 18 yards and an injury time penalty after a hand-ball
offence.
But there was no sneezing at Maradona's goal, a precise and opportunistic
left-foot shot from the edge of the penalty area that squeezed inside
Minou's right-hand goalpost.
He spent much of the first half on the turf, victim of close Greek marking
and his own theatrics, while Batistuta and Caniggia - another Argentine
coming off suspension for narcotics abuse - made most of the one-way
running. But, after the break, as Greece became tired and disheartened,
there were glimpses of the old surging Maradona runs and flicks.
Still, the Greeks were ancient, in the calendar sense, and it remains open
whether Maradona, playing in his fourth World Cup, can match the pace and
toughness of the Nigerians and Bulgarians in Argentina's remaining first
round matches.
</TEXT>
