<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 94 / Paris presses UN over Rwanda plan: Boutros Ghali supports
move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS AT THE UN, New York
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
France last night pressed a sceptical United Nations Security Council to
sanction the despatch of up to 2,000 French troops to Rwanda to protect
civilians caught in the vicious civil war.
Despite widespread opposition the plan is expected to be approved because it
has the backing of Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, UN secretary general, and no
one wants to be seen standing in the way of a humanitarian mission.
Mr Jean Bernard Merimee, the French delegate, says France seeks no political
or military advantage and the mission would be 'absolutely' protective.
He will have to spell out just how and where the troops would enter Rwanda
since the Patriotic Front rebels have promised to eject them.
The RPF vehemently opposes French involvement, because it says Paris
supports the Hutu-led government and militias widely regarded as responsible
for most killings.
Last night the RPF demanded the Security Council withdraw the small UN force
already in Rwanda if it approved the deployment of French troops.
In a letter to the Council Mr Gerald Gahima, the RPF representative at the
UN, said this was necessary because RPF forces might not be able to
distinguish between UN and other foreign troops. There are 450 Ghanaian
soldiers in Rwanda under a Canadian general.
In Rome, Mr Antonio Martino, Italian foreign minister, sharply criticised
the French proposal, voicing fears any white troops entering Rwanda would be
'torn to shreds'. In Geneva, the World Council of Churches urged France to
abandon the plan saying the entry of French troops would worsen the crisis
and make a solution even more difficult.
Mr Boutros Ghali, who discussed the crisis yesterday with Mr Douglas Hurd,
UK foreign secretary, is trying to assemble a 5,500-man all-African UN
force. Because of logistical problems he has told the Security Council it
would be impossible to have it in place in much under three months.
Ethiopia, Ghana, Senegal, Zambia, Zimbabwe, Congo, Malawi, Mali and Nigeria
have all offered infantry soldiers, but on condition equipment needs are met
by more affluent countries.
This will create further delays because the troops must be trained in the
use of unfamiliar equipment - another reason why the French plan may win
acceptance.
Editorial Comment, Page 23
</TEXT>
