<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Fresh setback for Dow as
dollar drops
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks suffered their second big setback in a row yesterday as a falling
dollar excited fresh concerns over the direction of monetary policy, writes
Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 34.88 down at 3,741.90, while the
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was 2.97 lower at 455.48. The
Nasdaq composite dropped 10.50, or 1.44 per cent, to 718.85 and the American
SE composite weakened 4.07 to 436.19.
Activity on the New York SE returned to a more sedate pace after a frenzied
'triple witching' session on Friday. Closing volume was a light 229.5m
shares and declining issues outpaced rises by 1,715 to 495.
The continued weakness of the dollar sent a shiver through US financial
markets, destroying any hopes that stocks would rally on the heels of
Friday's 34-point drop. The market often recovers strongly on the Monday
after a triple-witching rout, as the quarterly expiration of options and
futures tends to exaggerate any underlying trend.
Yesterday, however, bargain hunters were thin on the ground. Stocks were in
retreat from the opening bell amid fears that the Federal Reserve may have
no choice but to raise interest rates as early as next month to support the
slumping dollar.
The potential impact of such a move on the economy undermined any
inclination by the stock market to rally. Bonds were no help either, though
the Treasury market was buttressed by a softer tone in commodities.
Amid these cross-currents, economically sensitive stocks were leading share
prices in a determined march lower. Caterpillar, the heavy equipment
manufacturer, retreated Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 106 3/8 and Eaton, a
supplier of motor vehicle components, lost Dollars 1 5/8 at Dollars 52 3/8 .
Reynolds, the aluminium producer, shed Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 48, while
Bethlehem Steel fell Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 20 1/8 .
Among other Dow industrial issues, Sears Roebuck slipped Dollars 1 1/8 to
Dollars 47 5/8 . But Philip Morris put on Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 50 7/8
following news of the resignation of Mr Michael Miles, its chairman. He was
believed to be an advocate of a proposal to split the food and tobacco
businesses into separate companies.
US Healthcare jumped Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 43 1/8 on speculation that
Johnson &amp; Johnson was considering a takeover bid for the company, a pioneer
in the field of health maintenance organisations. J&amp;J held at Dollars 43 5/8
.
The Nasdaq gave up more ground as the technology sector stumbled again and
financial issues weakened. Cirrus Logic fell Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 28 3/8
and Atmel receded Dollars 2 3/4 to Dollars 23 1/4 .
Canada
Toronto shares moved sharply lower in line with other Canadian financial
markets yesterday after Prime Minister Jean Chretien failed to promise more
spending cuts.
Early in the day, Mr Chretien sent financial markets into a tailspin when he
played down the significance of reports that Ottawa may be forced to make
new spending cuts to stop the deficit from increasing due to rising interest
rates.
The TSE 300 composite index tumbled 68.3, or 1.64 per cent, to 4,088.4 and
falls overwhelmed advances by 649 to 162. A modest volume of 47.9m shares
was well below Friday's 60.6m. All 14 stock groups ended weaker, led by
industrial products and mining, which lost 2.63 and 2.31 per cent
respectively. The banking and energy stock groups were each off 1.33 per
cent, while golds shed 0.92 per cent.
</TEXT>
