<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / International Company News: Competition breaks up Nordic
banking co-operation venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Increasing cross-border competition within Nordic banking has led four of
the region's top banks to break up a 10-year-old co-operation deal.
The four - Unibank of Denmark, Union Bank of Finland, Den norske Bank of
Norway and Sweden's Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken - had handled each other's
interests in their respective markets under a venture called Scandinavian
Banking Partners.
At the height of the accord, they opened a joint venture in London called
the Scandinavian Banking Group, but this was bought out by SE-Banken in 1990
and merged with its existing London operation. Since then, the partnership
has been slimmed down to focus on a small range of business areas.
SE-Banken's move to open its own branches in Oslo and Helsinki, part of an
increasing trend among Nordic banks to move into neighbouring markets,
precipitated the decision finally to disband the partnership.
SE-Banken said no financial settlement was involved in the decision.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Unibank.
    Union Bank of Finland.
    Den norske Bank.
    Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DKZ  Denmark, EC.
    FIZ  Finland, West Europe.
    NOZ  Norway, West Europe.
    SEZ  Sweden, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6081 Foreign Banking and Branches and Agencies.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
