<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / Eurotunnel fall slims margin over rights price
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Falling global stock markets created further difficulties for Eurotunnel's
underwriters yesterday, as the registered shares fell a further 5p to 283p.
This left a 7 per cent premium to the 265p rights price, with just two
trading days before the Pounds 858m offer closes.
Underwriters said this was 'enough to encourage an adequate take-up', and
the nil paid shares, which stopped trading yesterday, stayed at 10p.
Traders spoke of further short selling by hedge funds, and said that since
it had become all but impossible to borrow Eurotunnel shares, short sellers
would have to buy back in the stock market, pushing the share price higher.
Mr Jean-Michel Plou, first vice president at Banque Indosuez, which led the
French underwriting, said: 'I am more pessimistic than I was a week ago, but
there are still grounds for optimism.'
French investors, who account for the bulk of the bearer units - 75 per cent
of Eurotunnel's issued shares - are not recompensed through a placing of the
rump of the issue and their take-up is usually much higher.
The institution with the most to lose is Swiss Bank Corp. SBC has Pounds
100m of the French portion of the underwriting, which carries the greatest
risk, since institutional investors do not tend to sub-underwrite their
exposure.
The French underwriting syndicate was led by Banque Indosuez, and includes
Banque Nationale de Paris, Banque Paribas and Credit Lyonnais, while the
British syndicate was led by Morgan Grenfell and SG Warburg, and includes
Robert Fleming and Salomon Brothers.
</TEXT>
